[
    {
        "content": "<p>The monadicity theorems and many other results about categories of Eilenberg-Moore algebras allow us to answer questions like: is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{D}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">D</span></span></span></span> a category of algebras over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span></span>? I am wondering if there has been similar results for Kleisli categories to answer questions like: is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{D}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">D</span></span></span></span> a category of free algebras over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 329716623,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1677158461
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A left adjoint is (up to isomorphism) the inclusion of a category into a Kleisli category if and only if it is bijective-on-objects.</p>",
        "id": 329738297,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1677163656
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This observation is due to Linton (e.g. \"Triples vs theories\"), but is stated more explicitly in Schumacher's <a href=\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01899590\">Minimale und maximale Tripelerzeugende und eine Bemerkung zur Tripelbarkeit</a>.</p>",
        "id": 329739813,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1677164007
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>:O wow!</p>",
        "id": 329803124,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677180734
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"hushed\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f62f\" role=\"img\" title=\"hushed\">:hushed:</span></p>",
        "id": 331123344,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1677186396
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>looking at this question from the point of view of \"categories as a language\" it becomes a nice piece of evidence that we still didn't learn to speak the language of <em>adjunctions</em>.</p>\n<p>if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T:{\\bf C}\\to {\\bf C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span></span></span></span> is a monad and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L\\dashv R:{\\bf X }\\to{\\bf C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">X</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span></span></span></span> any resolution of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> (i.e. an adjunction with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">RL=T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>). call <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bf K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">K</span></span></span></span></span> the kleisli category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>. then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">K</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>L</mi><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>L</mi><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\bf K}(a,b) \\cong {\\bf C}(a, Tb) \\cong {\\bf X}(La, Lb)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">K</span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">X</span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. so the kleisli category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> can be defined as the category with the objects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bf C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span></span></span> and the hom-sets of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bf X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">X</span></span></span></span></span> determined along <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> --- for <strong>any resolution of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> whatsoever</strong>. in other words, the kleisli category is obtained by taking the essentially-surjective/full-and-faithful factorization of any resolution of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>. (when you are given a concrete functor, the essentially-surjective boils down to identity-on-the-objects-functor, aka ioof...)</p>\n<p>but then you say \"doh, if i take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bf X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">X</span></span></span></span></span> to be the category of algebras, all that this says is that the kleisli category is the essential image of the free functor\". bien-sur. the only amazing thing about this fact is that it is not one of the first exercises in every textbook that includes monads.</p>\n<p>but we are pretty much blind to adjunctions. </p>\n<p>(plug: read dominic hughes' and my papers about the nucleus and the tight completions to see how much of the iceberg surfaces when the ocean of adjunctions is thickened just a little.)</p>",
        "id": 335048112,
        "sender_full_name": "dusko",
        "timestamp": 1677190411
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>the only amazing thing about this fact is that it is not one of the first exercises in every textbook that includes monads.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I completely agree. In fact, I have been slowly building up a collection of nice exercises for an introduction to category theory, and this was the very first one I added :)</p>",
        "id": 336358720,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1677192964
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>keep us posted about the exercises, whenever they get released :)</p>",
        "id": 336375329,
        "sender_full_name": "dusko",
        "timestamp": 1677201596
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"284005\">Ralph Sarkis</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Is.20my.20category.20a.20Kleisli.20category.20over.20C/near/329716623\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The monadicity theorems and many other results about categories of Eilenberg-Moore algebras allow us to answer questions like: is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{D}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">D</span></span></span></span> a category of algebras over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span></span>? I am wondering if there has been similar results for Kleisli categories to answer questions like: is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{D}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">D</span></span></span></span> a category of free algebras over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span></span></span></span>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>A possible related notion is \"abstract Kleisli categories\" or \"thunk-force categories\" <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/thunk-force+category\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/thunk-force+category</a></p>",
        "id": 336412034,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677224047
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Essentially, if a category is an \"thunk-force category\", then theres a special class of maps called the \"thunkable maps\". And on this subcategory of thunkable maps, there's an induced monad and the Kleisli category of the induced monad is equivalent to the starting \"thunk-force category\"</p>",
        "id": 336412449,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677224215
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Conversely, every Kleisli category of a monad is a \"thunk-force category\". But the subcategory of thunkable maps may not be equivalent the starting base category, but the resulting Kleisli category of the monad on thunkable maps is still equivalent to the first Kleisli category anyways.</p>",
        "id": 336412733,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677224345
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So \"thunk-force categories\" are precisely the Kleisli categories of monads, or alternatively a \"thunk-force category\" is a way of writing down a Kleisli category without a starting monad.</p>",
        "id": 336412883,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677224422
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277105\">JS PL (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Is.20my.20category.20a.20Kleisli.20category.20over.20C/near/336412883\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>So \"thunk-force categories\" are precisely the Kleisli categories of monads, or alternatively a \"thunk-force category\" is a way of writing down a Kleisli category without a starting monad.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Although this is only true for a specific subclass of monads, according to the nLab page.</p>",
        "id": 336447141,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1677235232
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"294557\">dusko</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Is.20my.20category.20a.20Kleisli.20category.20over.20C/near/335048112\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>in other words, the kleisli category is obtained by taking the essentially-surjective/full-and-faithful factorization of any resolution of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>. (when you are given a concrete functor, the essentially-surjective boils down to identity-on-the-objects-functor, aka ioof...)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>what do you mean by this? you factor the adjunction or just the left adjoint?</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"294557\">dusko</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Is.20my.20category.20a.20Kleisli.20category.20over.20C/near/335048112\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>but we are pretty much blind to adjunctions. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>alas...</p>",
        "id": 336488939,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677247001
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>what do you mean by this? you factor the adjunction or just the left adjoint?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You factor the left adjoint.</p>",
        "id": 336489128,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1677247057
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276092\">Nathanael Arkor</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Is.20my.20category.20a.20Kleisli.20category.20over.20C/near/336447141\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277105\">JS PL (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Is.20my.20category.20a.20Kleisli.20category.20over.20C/near/336412883\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>So \"thunk-force categories\" are precisely the Kleisli categories of monads, or alternatively a \"thunk-force category\" is a way of writing down a Kleisli category without a starting monad.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Although this is only true for a specific subclass of monads, according to the nLab page.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>What the nlab page is saying is that the construction monad ---&gt; thunk-force category ---&gt; monad gets you back to original monad when the monad is exact. I would still say thunk-force categories are indeed just Kleisli categories since:</p>",
        "id": 338067523,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677364561
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For any monad, its Kleisli category is a thunk-force category. Covnersely, every thunk-force category is the Kleisli category of an (exact) monad.</p>",
        "id": 338067650,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677364639
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyone curious about thunk-force/abstract categories, we talk about the coKleisli version in this paper of ours: <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2108.04304.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/2108.04304.pdf</a> (see Section 4, its about differential categories but if you're not interested in that, you can ignore those parts)</p>",
        "id": 338067791,
        "sender_full_name": "JS PL (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1677364721
    }
]